name: Gammel Strand
description: Gammel Strand, known as the 'old shore', is a historical landmark where seasonal fishermen first settled, evolving into a lively quay and market street. Today, it is a locally rooted, internationally oriented art center and cultural meeting point in the heart of Copenhagen. The exhibition program presents art that takes a critical and nuanced approach to the present, focusing on the big questions of our time – from the intimately personal to global dilemmas. Gammel Strand is also a platform for conversations, debates, and activities that bring people, art, and culture together in new communities.
price: Adult: 100kr, Under 27: 75kr, Under 16: Free, Groups bigger than 10: 75kr

name: Gammeltorv & Nytorv
description: Gammeltorv & Nytorv are original high-ground market squares that remain Copenhagen’s central public spaces. These squares are significant historical landmarks in the heart of Copenhagen, surrounded by elegant buildings and prominent institutions such as the Royal Theatre, Hotel D'Angleterre, and Kunsthal Charlottenborg. The area is known for its rich history dating back to the 17th century and features the oldest equestrian statue in Copenhagen, the statue of Christian V, erected in 1688.

name: Kongens Nytorv
description: Kongens Nytorv, or 'The King's New Square', is a historical landmark in the heart of Copenhagen's old town. It is the largest public square in the city, dating back to 1670, and was built by Christian V. The square is lined with prominent attractions such as the Royal Danish Theatre, Hotel D'Angleterre, Thott Palace, and Charlottenborg Palace, along with numerous restaurants and cafes. Originally used as a marketplace, it was transformed into a baroque garden complex in 1688, featuring a gilded equestrian statue of Christian V. In 1747, it was rebuilt as a military drill and ceremony ground for the King's troops until 1908, when it was reshaped to its original design.

name: Foundations of Absalon’s Castle
description: The Foundations of Absalon’s Castle are the remnants of a fortification built in 1167 by Bishop Absalon on the island of Slotsholmen in Copenhagen. The castle was constructed to protect the emerging city of Copenhagen and was surrounded by a curtain wall made of limestone from Stevns Cliffs. The castle stood for 200 years before being destroyed in 1369 by the Hanseatic League. Today, the remains of the curtain wall and some foundations of houses, along with a well made from hollowed-out oak trunks, are preserved in the cellars beneath Christiansborg Palace.

name: Rådhuspladsen & Metro excavations
description: Rådhuspladsen & Metro excavations offer a fascinating glimpse into Copenhagen's past, with underground displays of medieval church graves and wells near Strøget. The area surrounding Rådhuspladsen was once the town's most westerly district, featuring early fortifications, a moat, and the western gate, Vesterport. The Cityring Metro excavations provided new insights into the development of this part of the city from as early as c. A.D. 1050. The excavations took place from February 2011 till August 2012, revealing a wealth of new evidence about the city's origins and development.

name: Pilestræde well
description: Pilestræde well is a historical landmark in Copenhagen, representing a late 12th-century urban water supply feature that is visible in situ. It is located in the fashionable Pilestræde area, known for its stylish shops and Scandinavian design.

name: Øresund Bridge
description: The Øresund Bridge is a modern marvel that connects Denmark and Sweden, negotiating the shallow straits that first drew medieval traders. It is open 24 hours a day, 365 days a year, although special situations may arise due to wind, weather, maintenance, or accidents. The bridge is a significant engineering feat and a vital link between the two countries.

location.name: Øresund Bridge
location.address: Øresund Bridge, connecting Copenhagen, Denmark and Malmö, Sweden

name: Round Tower (Rundetårn)
description: The Round Tower (Danish: Rundetårn) is a 17th-century tower in Copenhagen, Denmark, built as an astronomical observatory. It features a unique equestrian staircase, a 7.5-turn helical corridor leading to a platform at the top, 34.8 meters above ground, offering panoramic views over Copenhagen. The tower houses the oldest functioning observatory in Europe, a telescope from 1929, and includes attractions such as the former library, now an exhibition hall, the attic of the bells, and a glass platform with a view over an 82-foot drop.

name: Amalienborg Palace
description: Amalienborg Palace is an 18th-century Rococo ensemble around an octagonal courtyard, noted for its symmetry and the equestrian statue of King Frederick V. It is the royal residence of the Danish monarchy and consists of four buildings where the royal family resides during the winter. Visitors can explore over 150 years of the history of the Royal House of Denmark and visit the Amalienborg Museum, which offers a behind-the-scenes look at the private interiors of the most recent kings and queens, along with an exhibit on the monarchy today. A prominent attraction is observing the Changing of the Royal Guard, a daily mid-morning spectacle.

name: Frederik’s Church (“The Marble Church”)
description: Frederik’s Church, also known as The Marble Church, is a large marble Baroque church in Copenhagen. It was a long-gestating project that began in 1740 and was finally completed in 1894. The church is renowned for its vast copper dome and is a popular venue for weddings, with bells ringing most weekends. Visitors can enjoy a magnificent view from the dome, which is accessible at 1pm every day during the summer months and on weekends for the rest of the year.

name: Grundtvig’s Church (Grundtvigs Kirke)
description: Grundtvig’s Church, also known as Grundtvigs Kirke, is a 20th-century brick expressionist masterpiece located in Copenhagen’s Bispebjerg district. It is renowned for its monumental vaults, light-yellow ribs, and a focus on human-scaled reverence. The church is an architectural symbol of Danish cultural history, featuring distinctive expressionist design, towering columns, and detailed workmanship. It is also a popular venue for weddings among locals.

name: The Royal Danish Library (“The Black Diamond”)
description: The Royal Danish Library, also known as 'The Black Diamond' due to its distinctive architectural profile, is a cultural site located in Copenhagen. It serves as Denmark's national library and the library for the University of Copenhagen. The 1999 waterfront extension is clad in black granite and glass, housing the free TREASURES exhibition of manuscripts and maps. The library also features a cafe, bookshop, and hosts exhibitions and concerts. Public tours are available on Saturdays for a fee.

location.name: The Royal Danish Library (“The Black Diamond”)

name: National Museum of Denmark
description: Denmark’s largest cultural-history museum, presenting a continuous timeline of Danish life from the Dark Ages to the modern era. The museum is organized chronologically and features stunning artifacts such as Viking helmets, the longest Viking ship in the world, and finely-crafted gold and silver jewelry.

name: Statens Museum for Kunst (SMK)
description: The National Gallery of Denmark (Statens Museum for Kunst) is Denmark’s official art gallery, featuring a rich and varied selection of Danish and international art from the past seven centuries. It houses exceptional works by renowned artists such as Pablo Picasso, Jean Metzinger, Henri Matisse, Edvard Munch, Mantegna, Nolde, Anna Ancher, Derain, Rubens, Hammershøi, Abramovic, Danh Vo, and Elmgreen & Dragset. The museum is a must-visit for art lovers, offering a blend of European classics and modern contemporary art. In addition to its art collections, SMK serves as an authorized tourist information point with multilingual staff ready to assist visitors.

name: Ny Carlsberg Glyptotek
description: Ny Carlsberg Glyptotek is one of Northern Europe’s most comprehensive sculpture galleries, founded by brewer Carl Jacobsen in 1897. It is an art and sculpture museum located in central Copenhagen, renowned for its marble sculptures and a stunning winter garden. The museum displays both ancient and modern art in unique surroundings, featuring high ceilings and a showstopping centrepiece winter garden full of palm trees surrounding a fountain and pond. The museum often holds special exhibitions that are integrated into the museum experience.

name: Rosenborg Castle & Treasury
description: Rosenborg Castle, built circa 1606 by King Christian IV as a Renaissance pleasure palace, served as a royal residence until 1710. Among the main attractions is the Knights' Hall with the coronation thrones, decorated with narwhal tusks, with three life-size silver lions standing guard.

name: Arken Museum of Modern Art
description: ARKEN Museum of Modern Art, located in Ishøj, south of Copenhagen, is renowned for its experimental, site-specific temporary exhibitions. The museum hosts a variety of exhibitions each year, showcasing modern Danish, Nordic, and international art, including both great classics and new names. ARKEN is situated in a scenic artificial landscape at Køge Bay Beach, featuring The Island of Art, a landscape of bridges, lagoons, and dunes. Since its inauguration in 1996, ARKEN has gained recognition for its collections, art exhibitions, and architecture, offering one of Scandinavia's finest collections of contemporary art.

name: Hallernes Smørrebrød, Torvehallerne
description: Hallernes Smørrebrød, located in the vibrant Torvehallerne market, offers a delightful culinary experience with its Classics Combo trio on rye. Torvehallerne is a beautiful indoor market made up of two glass halls filled with food stalls, coffee spots, and fresh produce stands, providing a clean and modern atmosphere.

name: Aamanns
description: Aamanns is a modern smørrebrød café located in the heart of Copenhagen, known for its innovative approach to traditional Danish food. The restaurant is committed to sustainability, with 60-90% of its produce being organic, earning it an official Silver mark from the Ministry of Food, Agriculture and Fisheries of Denmark. The interior features a light, modern design with high ceilings, terrazzo floors, and impressive brass chandeliers, complemented by old stone columns and church-like arches. Aamanns is renowned for serving some of the best smørrebrød in town, as well as gourmet dishes prepared with traditional ingredients in modern flavor combinations.

location.name: Østerbro/city centre
location.address: In the heart of Copenhagen, close to major tourist attractions

name: Restaurant Kronborg
description: Restaurant Kronborg is a charming eatery located in the Nyhavn cellar in Copenhagen, renowned for its traditional Danish dish, Frikadeller. It offers a cozy atmosphere and authentic Danish cuisine.

name: Jeanettes Pølser
description: Jeanettes Pølser is a traditional Danish hot dog stand located in the bustling city center of Copenhagen, specifically on Strøget. Known for serving classic Danish hot dogs, it is a popular spot for both locals and tourists looking to experience authentic Danish street food.

name: Torvehallerne
description: TorvehallerneKBH is a beautiful indoor market made up of two glass halls filled with food stalls, coffee spots, and fresh juice stalls. It is a food lover’s dream, offering a variety of culinary delights including pastries from Albatross og Venner and coffee from Coffee Collective.

name: Reffen Street Food Park
description: Reffen Street Food Park is a vibrant food park located in the re-purposed industrial area of Refshaleøen, Copenhagen. It offers a diverse selection of global food stalls and craft beer, providing a unique culinary experience. The park is situated over the river from the city center, making it a popular destination for both locals and tourists seeking a variety of foods and drinks from around the world.

name: Tivoli Food Hall
description: Tivoli Food Hall is Copenhagen's ultimate food destination, located right in Tivoli Gardens. It offers a gastronomic journey for the whole family with a variety of food stalls serving everything from juicy burgers and classic pizzas to authentic ramen and traditional Danish open-faced sandwiches. The food hall provides a cosy atmosphere with free access from the street and a direct entrance from Tivoli Gardens. Visitors can enjoy their meals in a cosy corner or take their favorite dishes to-go. The 850 square metre food hall is conveniently located next to Copenhagen Central Station and features 15 food stalls offering a wide range of high-quality foods from breakfast to dinner.

name: Coffee Collective
description: The Coffee Collective is much more than just good coffee and good service. They stay in close contact with the coffee farmers to ensure quality all the way from farm to cup. It started in 2007 with one small roastery and a strong desire to bring speciality coffee to Copenhagen. Now 17 years later, The Coffee Collective includes 8 coffee shops in Copenhagen and 1 in Aarhus. The Coffee Collective is widely recognised as one of the pioneers of the Scandinavian style of coffee bar design and roasting, with an emphasis on lighter roasts and more acidic coffees.

name: Andersen & Maillard
description: Andersen & Maillard is a combined café, roastery, and bakery located in a former bank space in the heart of Nørrebro, Copenhagen. Known for its exceptionally good coffee roasted on location and outstanding baked goods crafted by Milton Abel, a former pastry chef from Noma and Amass. The café offers a delightful experience with its heavenly croissants, bread served with home-churned butter and cheese, and even homemade soft-ice during the summer.

name: Darcy’s Kaffe
description: Darcy’s Kaffe is a cozy neighborhood coffee joint located on the corner of Rantzausgade in Copenhagen. Known for serving world-class coffee, Darcy’s Kaffe sources the best beans from top roasters around the globe. The café offers a constantly rotating menu of specialty beans, ensuring there is something for every coffee enthusiast. Alongside their exceptional coffee, they serve delicious pastries from Democratic Coffee and bread from Bageriet Brød. The owner, Darcy Millar, is passionate about sharing coffee knowledge with patrons, making it a welcoming spot for both coffee aficionados and casual visitors.

name: Roast Coffee
description: ROAST Coffee is an intimate espresso/filter café located in the cozy neighborhood of Islands Brygge, Central Copenhagen. It is renowned for its high-quality coffee, focusing on sustainability, quality, and fair working conditions for farmers. Founded by Andreas Astrup in 2014, ROAST aims to create a transparent channel for direct trade between coffee farmers and coffee lovers. The café roasts its beans directly in the shop, ensuring freshness and quality. Whether you prefer Cappuccino, Pour Over, or Espresso, the friendly staff is ready to guide you through their selection of flame-roasted beans.

name: Jolene
description: Jolene is a bottle-beer bar located in the Meatpacking District (Kødbyen) of Vesterbro, Copenhagen. Known for its inclusive and low-key atmosphere, Jolene has been a staple in the area for over a decade. It offers a relaxed, industrial-chic environment with shabby furniture and tattered lamps, where patrons can enjoy great music, affordable drinks, and a welcoming, LGBTQI+ friendly crowd. The bar features DJs spinning music throughout the night and occasionally hosts live rock bands. It's a place where you can dance like no one's watching and just be yourself.

name: Bakken
description: Bakken is a late-night club located in a repurposed warehouse in Vesterbro, Copenhagen. Known for its eclectic programming, it offers a vibrant nightlife experience. Note that Bakken is distinct from the world's oldest amusement park of the same name located north of Copenhagen.

name: Rust
description: Rust is a multi-stage, graffiti-clad venue located in Nørrebro, Copenhagen. It hosts a variety of music genres including indie-rock, dubstep, hip-hop, and electronica. On Fridays and Saturdays, Rust transforms into a nightclub with a multi-level dance floor.

name: Spillestedet Stengade
description: Spillestedet Stengade is a regional music venue in Copenhagen, featuring around 250 concerts a year. It offers a diverse range of music genres including rock, punk rock, pop, indie, hip hop, metal surf, electronica, dance, and more. The venue hosts a variety of clubbing events and is known for its unique vibe that attracts fans from long distances. Regular events include PlayIT/open jam sessions, Rocket Club concerts with up-and-coming bands, and RubA'Dub Sundays featuring reggae music.

name: Dupong
description: Dupong is a social ping-pong bar located in Nørrebro, Copenhagen. It is known for its very affordable beer and was created by four young students. The bar offers a relaxed setting where visitors can enjoy social games like ping-pong and table football (foosball) while mingling with locals and other visitors. The bar serves bottled beer, a few mixed drinks, and shots in disposable cups. It's a popular spot to start the night before heading to clubs.

name: Nyhavn canal-side pubs
description: Nyhavn is one of Copenhagen’s most iconic sights, known for its historic quayside taverns beautifully illuminated at night. Originally a commercial port, it was frequented by sailors visiting its pubs and alehouses. Today, the area is filled with renovated old houses, restaurants, and pavement cafes, offering a relaxed atmosphere with jazz music and great food. During Christmas, Nyhavn transforms with a festive market, decorated stalls, and twinkling lights, offering Danish Christmas delicacies.

name: Strøget small clubs
description: Strøget small clubs are clusters of late-night venues lining the main shopping street in Indre By, Copenhagen. These clubs offer a vibrant nightlife experience with a mix of pubs, live music venues, cocktail bars, and small clubs. The area is frequented by both locals and tourists, with the nightlife starting right after dinner and some clubs remaining open until 5 a.m. The district's nightlife is mainly youthful, with a variety of options for entertainment.

name: The Jane
description: The Jane is a Mad-Men–style cocktail lounge and nightclub located in the heart of Copenhagen on Gråbrødre Square. It offers a cozy lounge atmosphere with plush chairs and Chesterfields, as well as an electric nightclub vibe. The venue features a large bar, a fireplace, and hidden doors behind old bookshelves that reveal additional bars. Guests can enjoy a variety of upscale drinks, including a spicy twist on the classic margarita and a rich espresso martini with a hint of chocolate. A DJ plays around midnight for those who like to dance.

name: Copenhagen Light Festival
description: Copenhagen Light Festival features outdoor light installations and projections by Danish and international artists. From 31 January to 23 February, the harbour and city spaces are illuminated by beautiful light art and experiences from Nordhavn to Ørestad. Visitors can explore a tailor-made programme of light works and join guided tours on segways, canal boats, kayaks, or on foot.

name: Copenhagen Sakura Festival
description: Copenhagen Sakura Festival is a vibrant celebration of cherry blossoms in Copenhagen's Langelinie Park. The festival features Japanese cultural events such as dance performances, tea ceremonies, sumo displays, and artisan stalls. Visitors can enjoy drum shows, folk dance, martial arts, and workshops, or simply relax with a cup of tea while admiring the beautiful kimonos and the 200 cherry blossom trees in full bloom.

name: Copenhagen Beer Festival
description: The Copenhagen Beer Festival is a three-day event held at TAP1, showcasing Denmark’s historic and craft breweries alongside global brewers. The festival is organized into sessions, allowing attendees to experience a variety of beers from different breweries. It is open to everyone of age (18 years) and offers discounts for members of The Danish Beer Enthusiasts.

location.name: TAP1
location.address: Otto Busses Vej 5A, 2450 København SV, Denmark

name: Start! Festival
description: Start! Festival showcases emerging Danish musical talent on stages around Halmtorvet in Vesterbro, Copenhagen. It is a vibrant event that highlights the creativity and diversity of the local music scene, offering a platform for new artists to perform and gain exposure.

name: Roskilde Festival
description: Denmark’s largest culture and music festival just outside the city, featuring a diverse lineup of music acts and cultural events.

name: Copenhagen Cooking & Food Festival
description: Copenhagen Cooking & Food Festival is one of the biggest food festivals in Northern Europe, celebrating the love of food, seasonal produce, and high-quality ingredients. The festival offers a multi-day food-lovers’ paradise with workshops, long-table communal dinners, the Pizza Champion Cup, and a harbor gastro-cruise. It profiles Danish gastronomy by paying homage to its food culture, Nordic cuisine, and the major players on the gastronomic stage. The festival program is divided into several categories offering a plethora of gastronomic experiences and knowledge suitable for everyone’s taste, including 'Taste of emotion', 'Seasonal Nordic', 'Green Revolution', 'Food for children', and 'Copenhagen yards'.

name: Copenhagen Night of Culture—Kulturnatten
description: Copenhagen's annual Culture Night kicks off the autumn break in Copenhagen and offers children and adults hundreds of cultural events in just one night. Experience Copenhagen in a different light and see places you will not normally get access to, when hundreds of museums, churches, exhibition halls, art galleries, humanitarian organisations, political and cultural institutions open their doors to their secret rooms, basements, towers, and cultural events on this one night only. Whether you wish to experience the supreme court, parliament or simply take a stroll in the streets - Culture Night is simply beautiful. The whole city is an integral part of Culture Night, and the range of cultural institutions and venues mirrors how versatile Copenhagen is. There are hundreds of events for all ages, so do not hesitate to bring the kids to Culture Night in Copenhagen.

name: Copenhagen Irish Festival
description: Concerts, dance, open-jam sessions, and workshops celebrating Irish culture in concert halls and pubs citywide. The festival features sessions with both Danish musicians and booked Irish artists, live music in Irish pubs, a Gaelic mess organized by the Danish-Irish Society, and a film festival showcasing works from masters. It is held in the old meat market quarter, now a cultural hotspot.
